      <div xml:id="NA360-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">1. itu parattaiyiṉ pirinta (ET: pirintu vanta) talaimakaṉait tōḻi talaimakaḷ kuṟippaṟintu vāyiṉ maṟuttatu. 2. talaimakaḷ ūṭic colliyatūumām.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">1. This is how the confidante, knowing HER intention, refused the door to HIM who had separated for the sake of another woman. 2. It is also what SHE said in quarrel.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA360">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            muḻavumukam pularntu muṟaiyi ṉāṭiya</l>
<l>            viḻavoḻi kaḷatta pāvai pōla</l>
<l>            nerunaip puṇarntōr putunalam vauvi</l>
<l>            yiṉṟutaru makaḷir meṉṟōḷ peṟīiyar</l>
<l>            ceṉṟi peruma ciṟakkaniṉ parattai</l>
<l>            pallōr paḻitta ṉāṇi vallē</l>
<l>            kāḻiṟ kuttik kacintava ralaippak</l>
<l>            kaiyiṭai vaittatu meyyiṭait timiru</l>
<l>            muṉivuṭaik kavaḷam pōla naṉiperi</l>
<l>            tuṟṟaniṉ viḻuma muvappeṉ</l>
<l>            maṟṟuṅ kūṭu maṉaimaṭi tuyilē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>            You may go, great one,</l>
<l rend="indent">            to obtain the soft shoulder of women given today,</l>
<l rend="indent">            snatching the new innocence of those [you] united with yesterday,</l>
<l rend="indent2">            as the dolls of the floor<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kaḷatta pāvai</term>: this might either be taken literal, that is, real dolls, perhaps from a kind of doll theatre, or <term xml:lang="ta">pāvai</term> might refer to the female dancers that had performed at the festival.</note> staying behind after the festival,</l>
<l rend="indent2">            who danced in formation, the faces of the drums drying.</l>
<l rend="indent4">            May your other woman be excellent.</l>
<l>        I rejoice at your distress that [you] had in abundance,</l>
<l rend="indent2">            as the disgusting rice-ball [the young elephant?]<note place="foot">Here we seem to be facing the problem of an elliptical metaphor with unclear referential background. Most testimonies do not give a word for the elephant (<term xml:lang="ta">muṉi</term> is given as one by the TL on the basis of this passage), and the reading of ET clearly is the lectio facilior. Just as problematic is the word <term xml:lang="ta">kacintavar</term>. Without parallels, we cannot do much better than above.</note></l>
<l rend="indent2">            smears over [its] body from what it put in [its] trunk,</l>
<l rend="indent3">            when those relenting after poking [it] with a rod slap [it] –</l>
<l rend="indent">            being strongly ashamed that many blame [you].</l>
<l>        Relaxing sleep will come to the house again.(?)<note place="foot">The commentary understands here a promise for HIM in the future: he will be allowed to sleep here again. The impersonal mode of expression leaves room as well to HER falling asleep again when he has gone.</note></l>
        </lg>
      </div>
